Hello! Send us your CPF-related questions via text or voice message and we will strive to reply within 3 hours. If you have a case number, please let us know.
Hello Richard! Thanks for reaching out to CPF Board. My name is Matthew, and I'll be helping with your questions today.
I just like to confirm the accrued interest for the CPF still continue to grow even though I have completed the housing loan payment. Need to housing refund to stop it

Your understanding is correct. Interest will continue to accrue until a full refund for the amount is made. Accrued interest is the interest amount that you would have earned if your CPF savings had not been withdrawn for housing. The interest is computed on the CPF principal amount withdrawn for housing on a monthly basis (at the current CPF Ordinary Account interest rate) and compounded yearly.
Thanks and that is all.

Hi…I seems not able to find the part where we want Ed to pledge our house as part of RA…can I have the step by step procedure on how to apply or do I need to go to CPF board for it tks
I text Kok Siong yesterday regarding this 55 years old stuff

Hello! Thanks for reaching out to CPF Board. My name is Sheldon, and I’ll be helping with your questions today.\n\nFor verification purposes, may I have your full name please, so that I can check further?
Henry

Thank you for the verification. The Full Retirement Sum (FRS) for this year is $205,800, which you are able to meet. This amount will be transferred to your Retirement Account (RA). Any excess amount can be withdrawn from your Ordinary Account (OA).

You have the option to set aside your FRS using a combination of property (up to half the FRS) and cash. Additionally, you can withdraw your Retirement Account (RA) savings down to your Basic Retirement Sum (BRS*), which is $102,900, without pledging your property, provided that your expected housing refund is sufficient to restore your Full Retirement Sum (FRS). You can refer to this link for more information: cpf.gov.sg/member/faq/retirement-income/retirement-withdrawals/remaining-lease-ninety-five-withdraw-ra-savings-using-property. 

To make a withdrawal, you will need to wait until your 55th birthday. Once eligible, you can log in to the CPF website, navigate to the Retirement dashboard, and select Withdraw for immediate needs. Payment will be via Paynow or Interbank Giro.
My FRS ..I want to pledge 50% using housing  n cash 50%….how do I go about doing it…your chart show my FRS using cash from my OA n SA…I want to draw out more cash tks

You will need to wait until your 55th birthday before you can log in to the CPF website, navigate to the Retirement dashboard, and select Withdraw for immediate needs. This withdrawal allows you to withdraw from your Special Account, Ordinary Account, and Retirement Account.

By applying online, if you have PayNow service linked to your NRIC with your bank, you could receive the funds almost immediately, or if you prefer InterBank Giro, you will receive it within 5 working days instead.
Do take note, withdrawal of funds will come from your SA fully first then your OA.
If you have Singpass access, you may follow these steps for withdrawal:

Login to CPF website with your Singpass >
MyCPF >
MyRequest >
Retirement >
Withdraw CPF savings for immediate retirement needs >
Tick checkbox for ''Disclaimer'' >
Start >
Step 1: Indicate the amount you want to withdraw >
Next >
Step 2: Select PayNow (Linked via NRIC) or InterBank Giro (Provide Bank Account Details if required) >
Next >
Step 3: Check application details if correct and tick checkbox for ''Terms & Conditions'' >
Submit'
If any other questions arise, please feel free to chat us up any time within our office hours. Thank you for using this service.

Hello! Thanks for reaching out to CPF Board. My name is Jessica, and I’ll be helping with your questions today.\n\nMay I know what issues are you facing?
Would like to check if there are issues

Because during submitting.
There are two issues.

One employee name was keyed wrongly 

And other employee birthday only has the year on the ic.
What information do you need from me to check
May I have the company CSN number?

CPF contributions are credited to your employees based on the NRIC provided in your CPF submission.

Our new service helps to detect if the name of your new employee in the CPF submission, as shown in the “Mismatched Employee Details” section is different from his/her name indicated in their NRIC. 

If you have verified that you have paid CPF contribution to the intended employee and confirmed with your employee that the name is the same as what is shown on his/her NRIC, no further action is required from you. The mismatched employee’s name is only flagged out once in your Record of Payment.

As for employees with only birth year on the NRIC, you can indicate as 01/01/YYYY.

For further enquiries on CPF submission, you can reach out to Employer Hotline at 6220 2340, 8.30am-5.30pm, Monday-Friday, excluding weekends and public holidays.

Hospitals will be able to deduct from your Medisave account if prior authorizations are given. Usually in a case of a in-patient hospitalization, the authorizations are given during the admission process.

I want to come down on Friday morning. Can you give me a time

You may book an appointment via cpf.gov.sg/appt/oas/form , using the following steps by:

Tick ''I have read and accepted the Terms of Use.'' >
Start >
Identification type: ''Use NRIC or FIN number'' >
Key in your ''Use NRIC or FIN number'' >
Next >
Select the relevant category >
Select the relevant topic >
Select your preferred appointment type: ''Service Centre'' >
Indicate (Yes/No) if you have another person joining this appointment for additional enquiries? >
If yes, indicate their ID type and ID details. If no, continue next step >
Select your preferred Language (English, Chinese, Malay, Tamil) >
Select your preferred Service Centre (Bishan, Tampines, Jurong, Woodlands, Maxwell) >
Select your preferred date and time range >
Select your preferred available time slot >
Next >
Select mode of contact (Mobile/Email) so that the appointment details will be sent to this contact. Use the same contact details to view or reschedule your appointment later. >
Key in your contact details and press ''Get OTP'' >
Key in your OTP >
Next >
Review your appointment booking details >
Tick ''I have read and agreed to the Terms and Conditions.'' >
Submit to confirm your booking >
You will be informed that ''You have a confirmed appointment'' if successfully booked.

For tax rebate cash top up max is $8k for top up to self
Example 
My RA balance was 196k+ but now is 201k as at today (there was 4k interest as at 31 Dec 2023)
2024 FRS balance is 205,800
I logged in CPF and it showed me my available cash top up is 9k+
Shouldn’t my available cash top up for tax rebate to meet FRS be $4k instead of $9k? Doesn’t the recent 31 Dec interest earned 4k reduce my available cash top up?

In summary my question is does the 8k cash top to my RA FRS balance take into account any interest credited? 
Example 
RA balance 196k
Interest credited on 31 Dec 5k
Current RA balance 201k
2024 FRS sum 205,800
How much cash top up out of the $8k can I earn tax relief? 
Is it the full $8k or lesser due to the interest credit of 5k

Hello George! Thanks for reaching out to CPF Board. My name is Jasmine, and I’ll be assisting you today.

When computing the top-up limit to the Retirement Account (RA), the interest earned on your RA savings is excluded.

You can refer to our FAQ below for the details on how your top-up limit to your RA is computed:

cpf.gov.sg/member/faq/growing-your-savings/retirement-sum-topping-up-scheme/what-is-the-maximum-amt-of-top-ups-i-can-receive
Does this mean that I will enjoy the full tax relief of 8k if I top up cash to my RA even though my RA balance now is at 201k?\nThe 2024 FRS sum is 205,800

So long as you have available top-up limit to the current Full Retirement Sum (FRS), which you have checked and mentioned that your top-up limit to the FRS is $9k+, your cash top-up within the current FRS can enjoy tax relief.
Is there anything else I can assist you with today, George?

https://www.cpf.gov.sg/member/faq/growing-your-savings/cpf-interest-rates/how-much-extra-interest-can-i-earn-on-my-cpf-savings

Yes, for members who are above 55 where you have the RA , the additional interest given on the first $60k of your CPF savings is in the sequence of RA , OA (capped at $20K), SA and then MA.  So yes, you RA savings earns additional 2% on the first $30K and additional 1% on the second $30K.

I wish to declare my income for 2023. How to do this online.? Thks

Hello Alan! Thanks for reaching out to CPF Board. My name is Jasmine, and I’ll be assisting you today.

All self-employed Net Trade Income declarations for work done in 2023 (Year of Assessment 2024) are to be made with the Inland Revenue Authority of Singapore (IRAS) by filing a tax return.

There is no need to file separate declarations with CPF Board.

The income tax filing period is open from 1 March annually. If you have further enquiries on income tax filing matters, you can contact IRAS directly at iras.gov.sg/contact-us for their further advice.

You can also refer to our FAQ for more information on income declaration for self-employed persons: cpf.gov.sg/member/faq/growing-your-savings/self-employed-scheme/how-do-i-declare-my-annual-net-trade-income-online-as-a-self

Dear officer-in-charge,

I am writing with regards to CPF payment due to AW recalculation.

Hello Kang! Thanks for reaching out to CPF Board. My name is Jasmine, and I’ll be assisting you today.\n\nWe understand that you’re making a back payment to one of your employees. Hello Jasmine, as the employee is on unpaid leave, no salary payment was made to her. \nIn the month of Dec23, we are just paying the shortfall. \nIn this case, should we do a manual upload to state the additional wages subjected to CPF?
You can perform an additional submission via CPF EZPay instead of using FTP for your submission.
Okay noted

You can manually edit and pay the discrepancy together with your additional submission via CPF EZPay or pay to SkillsFuture Singapore Agency directly.

In this case, you can either submit the omitted amount with your next CPF submission, or make payment to SkillsFuture Singapore Agency directly.

Hello Chen! Thanks for reaching out to CPF Board. My name is Kenny, and I’ll be helping with your questions today.

I am over 55. I have 2 questions:

1.  I have balance in both my OA and SA. Can i just withdraw the balance in my OA leaving the balance in SA untouched?

2. After withdrawal, can i return to OA or SA account?

1.  I have balance in both my OA and SA. Can i just withdraw the balance in my OA leaving the balance in SA untouched?

If you have set aside your Full Retirement Sum, you can withdraw the available Ordinary and Special Account savings

2. After withdrawal, can i return to OA or SA account?

You will not be able to reinstate the amount that you have withdrawn. However, you can make voluntary contributions to three accounts i.e. Ordinary, Special and MediSave subject to the maximum limit for the year
For Q1 - i mean, can i just withdrawl my OA balance, without withdrawing the SA??
For Q2 - after i made a voluntary contribution,  can i withdraw at a later date again?
For Q1 - i mean, can i just withdrawl my OA balance, without withdrawing the SA?? -> You will not be able to do so as the default withdrawal sequence will be from your SA first followed by OA.
after i made a voluntary contribution,  can i withdraw at a later date again? -> Yes, you may do so.
You can visit (cpf.gov.sg/member/growing-your-savings/saving-more-with-cpf/top-up-ordinary-special-and-medisave-savings) for more information on making voluntary top-ups to three accounts
